com.camerontec.catalys.mis.eps.escalationpaths.runtime.actions

Interface IAction

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Cloneable, com.camerontec.catalys.mis.eps.IPersistable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractAction, BaseSNMPAction, SampleSNMPAction

    public interface IAction
extends Cloneable, com.camerontec.catalys.mis.eps.IPersistable
    An action that can be taken as part of an escalation level in an escalation path. Implementation of IAction should have a constructor with no arguments, else the initialisation will fail. All implementations of the underlying IPersistable interface must write and read properties returned by the getActionProperties(). This is needed for retrieving the actions info after a restart.
    Author:
    Jairam Gottapu

      • getSupportedPropertyNames

        Set<String> getSupportedPropertyNames()
        Must return all the supported property names for the action. If any of the properties contains a property that is not in the list of supported properties, the action will fail to initialise.
        Returns:
        Set of all the supported property names

      • getMandatoryPropertyNames

        Set<String> getMandatoryPropertyNames()
        Must return a list of all the mandatory property names for the action, without which the configuration of the action must fail.
        Returns:
        Set of all the mandatory property names

      • setActionProperties

        void setActionProperties(Map<String,String> actionProperties)
        Set the properties for this action. Properties are usually set during initialization of the action via the dashboard or when reading the properties from persistence after a restart. One can augment these properties if needed for custom action implementations. This will always be invoked before executeAction(ActionSourceEvent).
        Parameters:
        actionProperties - properties of the action

      • initialize

        void initialize()
        Performs the necessary initialization of this action. This may involve validating the action's properties, allocating resources, etc. Any exception thrown by the implementation of this method will cause the MIS to refuse to start This will always be invoked before executeAction(ActionSourceEvent).
